						<div class="row">
							<div class="twelve columns">
								<p class="lead">The computers that people commonly use today can be divided into two kinds:</p>
								<br />
								

<dl class="nice contained tabs">
						<dd><a href="#nice1" class="active">Desktop Computer</a></dd>
			<dd><a href="#nice2">Laptop Computer</a></dd>
								</dl>
								
					<ul class="nice tabs-content contained">
					<li class="active" id="nice1Tab">
										<div class="row">
											<div class="six columns">
												


<p>A <strong> Desktop Computer</strong> is a computer that is not made to be easily moved. The components are in three or more separate pieces (also called components) that are connected. It can be used in your office or other desk/study area.</p>	

															<p>This example has 4 separate, but connected, components.</p>

											
											<ol>
												<li><strong>Monitor</strong></li>
												<li><strong>Keyboard</strong></li>
												<li><strong class="define" title="A pointing device for the computer">Mouse</strong></li>
												<li><strong>Tower with Hard Drive or C: Drive</strong></li>
											</ol>
											
										</div>
										<div class="six columns">
											<img src="images/fig1.jpg" alt="Computer Diagram">
			



											</div>
										</div>
										  </li>
								  <li id="nice2Tab">
									<div class="row">
										<div class="six columns">
											

												<p>A <strong> Laptop Computer</strong> is a computer that is made to be easily moved. It has the same four pieces (components) as a desktop but they are all in one unit.</p>
												
												<ol>
													<li><strong> Monitor/Screen</strong></li>
													<li><strong>Keyboard</strong></li>
													<li><strong>Mouse</strong> (touch pad in this picture)</li>
													<li><strong>Hard Drive or C:</strong></li>
												</ol>
												
											</div>
											<div class="six columns">
												<img src="images/misc/computer_laptop.png" alt="Laptop Diagram">







							</div>
									</div>
								  </li>
								</ul>
							
							</div>
						</div>	
						
						<br />
							<p>Whether you have a desktop or laptop, your computer will have:</p>						<div class="row">
							<div class="six columns">
								
								<ul class="circle">
									<li><strong>Screen:</strong> The screen is what you look at to view information on your computer. On a desktop, the screen is the front part of the monitor, which is a separate component and can look like a TV screen. A <b>Touch Screen</b> is equipped with sensors to allow you to interact with the computer by touching the screen with one or more fingers.<p style="margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in; margin-left: .5in; margin-bottom: 10.0pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo1; text-align: justify; line-height: 115%; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif;">
                                        <o:p></o:p></p>
                                    </li>
									<li><strong>Keyboard:</strong> The keyboard has buttons or keys with letters, numbers and symbols for you to type information into your computer. (more information later in this section)</li>
								</ul>
</div>
						
							<div class="six columns">
								<ul class="circle">
									<li><strong>Mouse:</strong> Both desktop and laptop computers have a mouse, a pointing device. (more information later in this section). In a desktop, it is separate and in a laptop it is on the keyboard.</li>
									<li><strong>Hard Drive or C: Drive:</strong> This drive is a storage location for information that is built-in to your computer (more information later in this section) and is either located in a box called a tower (on a desktop) or underneath the keyboard (on a laptop).</li>
								</ul>
								
							</div>
						</div>		

